

=============================
Domain Electrochemistry Terms
=============================


Electrochemistry Domain Ontology (ECHO)
=======================================



This reference module contains the core terms for the electrochemistry domain.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_58a20764_c339_4856_983a_05092b5282e8"></div>

ACVoltammetrySignal
-------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_58a20764_c339_4856_983a_05092b5282e8

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">Sinusoidal potential waveform superimposed to a linear potential ramp.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7'; return false;}">ElectricPotentialSignal</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

AcidicElectrolyte
-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_6592d8cc_4ce4_42ca_b010_6bfc4a8444d2

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">AcidicAqueousElectrolyte; AcidicSolution</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">an aqueous electrolyte with a nominal pH values less than 7</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_b812e9d0_7c58_4455_b3e7_6847f10c8e8a' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_b812e9d0_7c58_4455_b3e7_6847f10c8e8a')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b812e9d0_7c58_4455_b3e7_6847f10c8e8a'; return false;}">AqueousElectrolyte</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_334b3acd_e35d_4d5a_b8b5_6d13cbebbc57' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_334b3acd_e35d_4d5a_b8b5_6d13cbebbc57')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_334b3acd_e35d_4d5a_b8b5_6d13cbebbc57'; return false;}">SulfuricAcidSolution</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_78f75a64_55b6_4243_a35e_3d279c83209b' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_78f75a64_55b6_4243_a35e_3d279c83209b')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_78f75a64_55b6_4243_a35e_3d279c83209b'; return false;}">PhosphoricAcidSolution</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   typical alkaline electrolytes have a pH in the range 0 < x < 4

.. admonition:: Example

   HCl-H2O

ActivationEnergyOfChargeCarrierDiffusivityInElectrolyte
-------------------------------------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_56de36fe_e8e1_486c_8d29_061ac8d28c13

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the activation energy barrier in an Arrhenius expression for the diffusivity of lithium in an electrolyte</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">bpxKey</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">['Parameterisation','Electrolyte','Diffusivity activation energy [J.mol-1]']</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">cidemodKey</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">['electrolyte','diffusion_constant','arrhenius','activation_energy']</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_d7f8cab9_b035_4ecd_be63_292672572526' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_d7f8cab9_b035_4ecd_be63_292672572526')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d7f8cab9_b035_4ecd_be63_292672572526'; return false;}">ActivationEnergy</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   this is a very specific term with a narrow conceptualization, used mostly as an anchor term for supporting interoperability; a more general term is suitable in most cases.

-----------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_7fa406b0_512a_4d59_9e0c_5d8aba0103ae

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">ActivationPolarization</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">part of the electrode polarization arising from a charge-transfer step of the electrode reaction</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-05' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-05')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-05'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-05</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_1cd1d777_e67b_47eb_81f1_edac35d9f2c6' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_1cd1d777_e67b_47eb_81f1_edac35d9f2c6')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_1cd1d777_e67b_47eb_81f1_edac35d9f2c6'; return false;}">Overpotential</a></td>

ActiveElectrode
---------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9a823d64_9d10_4a29_9cbd_9bbdad7985bc

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">NonInertElectrode; ReactiveElectrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">an electrode which is chemically altered by the electrode reaction</td>

    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_c995ae70_3b84_4ebb_bcfc_69e6a281bb88' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_c995ae70_3b84_4ebb_bcfc_69e6a281bb88')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_c995ae70_3b84_4ebb_bcfc_69e6a281bb88'; return false;}">ElectricCurrent</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalControlQuantity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_f591a444_89d6_4093_836d_7d53895edce4"></div>

AmplitudeOfAlternatingVoltage
-----------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f591a444_89d6_4093_836d_7d53895edce4

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">half of the peak-to-peak amplitude of a periodic voltage perturbation within a single time period, with respect to a reference potential value</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.A00311' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.A00311')){window.location.href='https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.A00311'; return false;}">https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.A00311</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_4f2d3939_91b1_4001_b8ab_7d19074bf845' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_4f2d3939_91b1_4001_b8ab_7d19074bf845')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_4f2d3939_91b1_4001_b8ab_7d19074bf845'; return false;}">ElectricPotential</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalControlQuantity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   This term should denote half of the peak-to-peak amplitude. Peak-to-peak and r.m.s. amplitudes should be so specified.

   <div id="electrochemistry_b6319c74_d2ce_48c0_a75a_63156776b302"></div>

Anode
-----

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b6319c74_d2ce_48c0_a75a_63156776b302

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">by convention, cell electrode at which an oxidation reaction occurs</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">etymology</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">From Greek anodos (way up). Chosen to denote the electrode associated with the upward path of current by convention; later anchored by usage to the site of oxidation.Coined by Michael Faraday with guidance from William Whewell and Whitlock Nicholl.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q181232' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q181232')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q181232'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q181232</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anode' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anode')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anode'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00370' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00370')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00370'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00370</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-27' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-27')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-27'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-27</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">dbpediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://dbpedia.org/page/Anode' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://dbpedia.org/page/Anode')){window.location.href='https://dbpedia.org/page/Anode'; return false;}">https://dbpedia.org/page/Anode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The anode is the negative electrode during discharge and the positive electrode during charge.

.. warning::

   The term "anode" is often used interchangably with "negative electrode" even though it only applies while the cell is being discharged. When the cell is being charged the positive electrode becomes the anode.

.. important::

   IEC and IUPAC recommend defining anode/cathode by oxidation/reduction rather than by polarity or charge sign.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_565c0b10_70fe_441a_b76a_b9a8e08ca7b7"></div>

Anolyte
-------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_865a40fc_2187_4549_a7e1_37aa2458448f

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrolyte on the anode side of an electrochemical cell that is divided into compartments</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">etymology</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">From Greek anodos ('way up') + lyts (, looser)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-19' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-19')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-19'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-19</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59'; return false;}">Electrolyte</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Electrolyte solution in the anodic compartment of an electrolysis cell or galvanic cell, i.e., in that part of the cell where the anode is placed.


----

AreicCapacity
-------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_bcb33f7e_5573_4bc2_b636_4ea313a9dd3a

  <table class="element-table">

    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_4ebe2ef1_eea8_4b10_822d_7a68215bd24d' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_4ebe2ef1_eea8_4b10_822d_7a68215bd24d')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_4ebe2ef1_eea8_4b10_822d_7a68215bd24d'; return false;}">CellVoltage</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalControlQuantity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. admonition:: Example

   in EIS, an alternating voltage signal is superimposed to a baseline voltage, which can be the open circuit potential or a fixed cell voltage

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a model for the double layer that includes the action of the solvent on the surface</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b'; return false;}">DoubleLayerModel</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   proposed by John Bockris, M. A. V. Devanathan, and Klaus Mueller in 1963

ButlerVolmerEquation
--------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d48ea516_5cac_4f86_bc88_21b6276c0938

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">ButlerVolmerApproximation; ErdeyGruzVolmerEquation</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a phenomenological model for electrode kinetics, describing the relation between the electrode current from an electrochemical charge-transfer reaction and the surface overpotential of the electrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903846' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903846')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903846'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903846</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butler%E2%80%93Volmer_equation' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butler%E2%80%93Volmer_equation')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butler%E2%80%93Volmer_equation'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butler%E2%80%93Volmer_equation</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">dbpediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://dbpedia.org/page/Butler%E2%80%93Volmer_equation' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://dbpedia.org/page/Butler%E2%80%93Volmer_equation')){window.location.href='https://dbpedia.org/page/Butler%E2%80%93Volmer_equation'; return false;}">https://dbpedia.org/page/Butler%E2%80%93Volmer_equation</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalRelation</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   i = i0 * (exp(alpha*n*F*eta/(R*T))  exp(-(1-alpha)*n*F*eta/(R*T)))

    <td class="element-table-value">a non-woven mat of randomly oriented carbon fibers, providing excellent thermal insulation, chemical resistance, and high surface area for various industrial and electrochemical applications</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_ec7464a9_d99d_45f8_965b_4e9230ea8356' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_ec7464a9_d99d_45f8_965b_4e9230ea8356')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_ec7464a9_d99d_45f8_965b_4e9230ea8356'; return false;}">ManufacturedMaterial</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>

  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   These electrodes can easily be chemically modified by the incorporation of reagents (electrocatalysts, redox mediators, complexation agents, enzymes, etc.) and by the attachment of micro- or nanoparticles to prepare electrochemical sensors for analytical applications.

.. note::

   Typical composition of a carbon ink expressed as mass fractions is graphite powder 60 % and polystyrene 40 %.

CarbonPasteElectrode
--------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b0a0dddb_d942_4af2_b6a7_d7165f4253f1

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">CPE</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">Electrode of a composite of carbon powder and a pasting liquid (including mineral oil, Nujol, bromoform, bromonaphthalene).</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q5037987' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q5037987')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q5037987'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q5037987</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_paste_electrode' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_paste_electrode')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_paste_electrode'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_paste_electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543'; return false;}">InertElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_ec6f3d6f_bdf5_418f_9314_3ef2ff528103' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ec6f3d6f_bdf5_418f_9314_3ef2ff528103')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ec6f3d6f_bdf5_418f_9314_3ef2ff528103'; return false;}">CarbonInkElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The CPE was first described by Adams in 1958. A CPE is typically housed in a Teflon holder, contacted by a conductive wire (occasionally a piston is used to renew the surface by extrusion of the used paste). Problems are long-term stability of the paste and that the binder can influence its properties.

.. note::

   These electrodes can easily be chemically modified by the incorporation of reagents (electrocatalysts, redox mediators, complexation agents, enzymes, etc.) and by the attachment of micro- or nanoparticles to prepare electrochemical sensors for analytical applications.

Cathode
-------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_35c650ab_3b23_4938_b312_1b0dede2e6d5

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">by convention, cell electrode at which, a reduction reaction occurs</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">etymology</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">From Greek kathodos (way down). Intended to name the electrode on the downward path of current by convention; in modern usage the site of reduction. Coined by Michael Faraday with support from William Whewell and Whitlock Nicholl.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q175233' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q175233')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q175233'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q175233</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathode' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathode')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathode'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C00905' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C00905')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C00905'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C00905</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-03' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-03')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-03'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-03</a>; <a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-28' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-28')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-28'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-28</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">dbpediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://dbpedia.org/page/Cathode' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://dbpedia.org/page/Cathode')){window.location.href='https://dbpedia.org/page/Cathode'; return false;}">https://dbpedia.org/page/Cathode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The cathode is the positive electrode during discharge and the negative electrode during charge.

.. warning::

   The term "cathode" is often used interchangably with "positive electrode" even though it only applies while the cell is being discharged. When the cell is being charged the negative electrode becomes the cathode.

.. important::

   IEC and IUPAC recommend defining anode/cathode by oxidation/reduction rather than by polarity or charge sign.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_f8e0d532_cf44_403c_9188_e00ee161a3c1"></div>

CathodeElectrolyteInterphase
----------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f8e0d532_cf44_403c_9188_e00ee161a3c1

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a type of solid electrolyte interface that forms on the surface of the electrode designated as the "cathode" or positive electrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_ecf136cb_2584_4cb1_98b7_2d2b3d22e40d' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ecf136cb_2584_4cb1_98b7_2d2b3d22e40d')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ecf136cb_2584_4cb1_98b7_2d2b3d22e40d'; return false;}">SolidElectrolyteInterphase</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   used to distinguish the interphase on the cathode surface from that on the anode, which is typically called the solid electrolyte interphase (SEI)

.. note::

   electrode reaction involving an electrochemical reduction

   electrode reaction, where the energy of electrons in the working electrode is higher than the LUMO orbital of the substrate

Catholyte
---------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_15b852b5_19cc_49ab_849f_7df6175fb2be

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrolyte on the cathode side of an electrochemical cell that is divided into compartments.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">etymology</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">From Greek kathodos ('way down') + lyts (, looser)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-18' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-18')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-18'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-18</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59'; return false;}">Electrolyte</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Electrolyte solution in the cathodic compartment of an electrolysis cell or galvanic cell, i.e., in that part of the cell where the cathode is placed.

  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Cell voltage fluctuates based on factors such as applied current, internal resistance, temperature, and composition.

.. note::

   Cell voltage represents the instantaneous electrical potential difference between the positive and negative electrodes of an electrochemical cell. It is a key parameter for monitoring battery performance, estimating state-of-charge, and diagnosing potential failures.

----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a5962e05_466d_46a4_8951_bea59d7326e5

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>

  </tr>

ChargingCRate
-------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a7dc73e2_d4aa_4dfc_8b4d_cb611f1501fb

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">[an indicator of the] electric current at which a secondary cell or battery is charged</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-45' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-45')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-45'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-45</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_e1fd84eb_acdb_4b2c_b90c_e899d552a3ee' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_e1fd84eb_acdb_4b2c_b90c_e899d552a3ee')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_e1fd84eb_acdb_4b2c_b90c_e899d552a3ee'; return false;}">CRate</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   the charge rate is expressed as the reference current It = Cr/n where Cr is the rated capacity declared by the manufacturer and n is the time base in hours for which the rated capacity is declared

ConcentrationCell
-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_8a5083b0_cd23_4f8c_99e8_b9ccd6f9f3a2

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrochemical cell that has two half-cells separated by a wall permeable to ions, both containing the same electrolyte differing only in their ion concentrations</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903563' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903563')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903563'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903563</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concentration_cell' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concentration_cell')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concentration_cell'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concentration_cell</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-08' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-08')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-08'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-08</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">illustration</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/emmo-repo/domain-electrochemistry/dev/docs/assets/img/fig/png/ConcentrationCell.png"><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/emmo-repo/domain-electrochemistry/dev/docs/assets/img/fig/png/ConcentrationCell.png" alt="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/emmo-repo/domain-electrochemistry/dev/docs/assets/img/fig/png/ConcentrationCell.png" style="max-width:400px; max-height:300px;"/></a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalDevice</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   a concentration cell produces a voltage as it attempts to reach equilibrium, which will occur when the concentration in both cells is equal.

ConcentrationOverpotential
--------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9ed7210c_c4fa_467b_822d_ba12f885bdf4

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">ConcentrationPolarization; MassTransferOverpotential; MassTransferPolarization</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">The concentration overpotential of an electrode reaction at a given electrode current density (c.d.) is basically the difference in equilibrium potentials across the diffusion layer. More precisely, it is the potential of a reference electrode (of the same electrode reaction as the working electrode ) with the interfacial concentrations which establish themselves at c.d., relative to the potential of a similar reference electrode with the concentrations of the bulk solution. From such a measured potential difference, with c.d. flowing, one needs to subtract the ohmic potential drop prevailing between the two electrodes.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#Concentration_overpotential' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('Concentration_overpotential')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overpotential#Concentration_overpotential'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overpotential#Concentration_overpotential</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C01230' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C01230')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C01230'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C01230</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-08' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-08')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-08'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-08</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_1cd1d777_e67b_47eb_81f1_edac35d9f2c6' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_1cd1d777_e67b_47eb_81f1_edac35d9f2c6')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_1cd1d777_e67b_47eb_81f1_edac35d9f2c6'; return false;}">Overpotential</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

ConductivityCell
----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b525a629_a679_464f_bc5b_b49d2fc82686

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a device used in electrochemistry to measure the resistance of a solution to determine its conductivity</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalDevice</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Formed, in theory, by two 1 cm2 reversible electrodes spaced 1 cm apart, providing a uniform distribution of electrical field. In practice, however, a number of other configurations are used.


----

Connector
---------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d8a78cd2_8107_46dd_a198_0b64676efc00

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">conductor of electricity used for carrying current between components in an electric circuit</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-37' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-37')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-37'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-37</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_f76884f7_964e_488e_9bb7_1b2453e9e817' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_f76884f7_964e_488e_9bb7_1b2453e9e817')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_f76884f7_964e_488e_9bb7_1b2453e9e817'; return false;}">Component</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. admonition:: Example

   a connector electrically joins two cells, or a terminal of a cell to a terminal of the battery, or a terminal of the battery to an exterior circuit and also to auxiliary devices

ConstantCurrentCharging
-----------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_83f2b1e9_cb67_4dbf_977f_ba54bbae374f

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">GalvanostaticCharging</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>

ConstantCurrentChargingCapacity
-------------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_37c38b7e_9ded_481a_85fd_a467f1ee2b9f

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">ConstantCurrentChargeCapacity</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the capacity obtained during constant current charging of an electrochemical device</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">typicalUnit</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#AmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('AmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour</a>; <a href='#MilliAmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('MilliAmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">hiddenLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">CC-Cap; CC-Cap/mAh</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_10763eb0_dbc9_4d34_bd1a_7b8996590d45' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_10763eb0_dbc9_4d34_bd1a_7b8996590d45')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_10763eb0_dbc9_4d34_bd1a_7b8996590d45'; return false;}">ChargingCapacity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Constant current charging capacity is often used to assess device performance and state-of-health. In a CC-CV charging process, if this value is significantly lower than the rated capacity under the same conditions, it may indicate underlying limitations. A decline over multiple cycles can be a sign of degradation.


----

ConstantCurrentConstantVoltageCharging
--------------------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0cc8f231_0ce5_467e_9c76_29b2c80349ad

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a two-step charging process in which a constant current is applied until a set upper cutoff voltage is reached and then the cell is potentiostatically held at that voltage until the current falls below some set threshhold value</td>

Coulometer
----------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_fb9bf7cb_dd4b_4391_99a1_628263dd6940

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">Voltameter</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">measuring instrument to obtain the electrical charge passed in an experiment, or to produce a known amount of substance in a titration.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q905539' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q905539')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q905539'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q905539</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voltameter' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voltameter')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voltameter'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voltameter</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">dbpediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://dbpedia.org/page/Voltmeter' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://dbpedia.org/page/Voltmeter')){window.location.href='https://dbpedia.org/page/Voltmeter'; return false;}">https://dbpedia.org/page/Voltmeter</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_f2d5d3ad_2e00_417f_8849_686f3988d929' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_f2d5d3ad_2e00_417f_8849_686f3988d929')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_f2d5d3ad_2e00_417f_8849_686f3988d929'; return false;}">MeasuringInstrument</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Modern instruments for measuring trace water by Karl Fischer titration use the passage of a measured charge to produce iodine from iodide solution. They are known as Karl Fischer coulometers

.. note::

   The silver coulometer is a primary reference measurement procedure [VIM 2.8] for charge and current. By weighing the mass of silver deposited in a known time at constant current, the charge and current are calculated from Faradays laws of electrolysis


----

CounterElectrode
----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_871bc4a4_2d17_4b88_9b0f_7ab85f14afea

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">AuxiliaryElectrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrode whose function is to carry the electric current flowing through the electrical circuit of an electrochemical cell, the electrochemical processes on its surface not being of interest</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00535' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00535')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00535'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00535</a></td>

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   An auxiliary electrode is used in any three-electrode cell, together with a working electrode and reference electrode.

.. note::

   An auxiliary electrode must not add an excessive potential burden to the cell. It is chosen for the efficiency of the electrochemical reaction and usually has a greater surface area than the working electrode.


----

.. raw:: html

CurrentPotentialPlot
--------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b9a72491_8a50_4cac_a131_1e95d72b57ee

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">CurrentPotentialCurve; ElectricCurrentPotentialCurve</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">plot of current versus applied potential (I-E) for a given system</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_ddade648_2033_47b6_bc36_b562a9af591e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ddade648_2033_47b6_bc36_b562a9af591e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ddade648_2033_47b6_bc36_b562a9af591e'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalPlot</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_bbae1ef4_0a95_4e7d_9932_1bf939129eef' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_bbae1ef4_0a95_4e7d_9932_1bf939129eef')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_bbae1ef4_0a95_4e7d_9932_1bf939129eef'; return false;}">Voltammogram</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The curve is sigmoidal in hydrodynamic voltammetry, voltammetry at microelectrodes and polarography, or peak-shaped in ac voltammetry, differential pulse voltammetry, square- wave voltammetry, stripping voltammetry, and derivative techniques.

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_472a0ca2_58bf_4618_b561_6fe68bd9fd49' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_472a0ca2_58bf_4618_b561_6fe68bd9fd49')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_472a0ca2_58bf_4618_b561_6fe68bd9fd49'; return false;}">Procedure</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_cb223440_51bd_4f16_a536_96ec408e7de4' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_cb223440_51bd_4f16_a536_96ec408e7de4')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_cb223440_51bd_4f16_a536_96ec408e7de4'; return false;}">FormationCycling</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_5a5ef74b_e4a7_4b85_ab21_ae0febebaf58' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_5a5ef74b_e4a7_4b85_ab21_ae0febebaf58')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_5a5ef74b_e4a7_4b85_ab21_ae0febebaf58'; return false;}">PotentiostaticCycling</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_79a8802e_8296_459a_b65d_6e5c79e1bf37' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_79a8802e_8296_459a_b65d_6e5c79e1bf37')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_79a8802e_8296_459a_b65d_6e5c79e1bf37'; return false;}">GalvanostaticCycling</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_ac6c2371_995a_4fcb_89a2_15cb6615741e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ac6c2371_995a_4fcb_89a2_15cb6615741e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ac6c2371_995a_4fcb_89a2_15cb6615741e'; return false;}">ConstantCurrentConstantVoltageCycling</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   in a secondary battery these operations may consist of a sequence of a discharge followed by a charge or a charge followed by a discharge under specified conditions

.. note::

   this sequence may include rest periods

DifferentialPotentialPulse
--------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b49e2355_392f_4e83_b630_7ff4581d767b

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">Small pulses of electric potential superimposed to a linear potential ramp or a staircase potential ramp.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7'; return false;}">ElectricPotentialSignal</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The pulses are usually of constant height 10 to 100 mV and constant width 10 to 100 ms.

-------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_885b462e_f6bc_412d_8b94_9425e13af0c7

  <tr>

  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>

  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   I_{DC}

.. note::

   The term direct current should be used where there is ambiguity concerning the constancy of direction of current. See alternating current.

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b

  <table class="element-table">

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">model representing the structure of an electrolyte at an electrode-electrolyte interface by a rigid layer formed by the charge carriers on the surface of the electrode and a diffuse layer formed by mobile ions in the electrolyte.</td>

   <div id="electrochemistry_b76a778f_253f_4210_a67f_fb6444d0de26"></div>

DroppingMercuryElectrode
------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b76a778f_253f_4210_a67f_fb6444d0de26

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">DME</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">mercury electrode formed by sequence of mercury drops falling from a small aperture</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q962292' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q962292')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q962292'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q962292</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dropping_mercury_electrode' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dropping_mercury_electrode')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dropping_mercury_electrode'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dropping_mercury_electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_df78745e_f9db_4830_88f0_8ce074fcb8ff' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_df78745e_f9db_4830_88f0_8ce074fcb8ff')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_df78745e_f9db_4830_88f0_8ce074fcb8ff'; return false;}">MercuryElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Other kinds of mercury drop electrodes are the static mercury drop electrode (SMDE), in which a drop is held at constant radius before being mechanically knocked off, and the hanging mercury drop elec- trode (HMDE), in which the whole experiment is performed on a single drop of mercury.

.. note::

   The DME was introduced by Jaroslav Heyrovsk (1890  1967). A drop is renewed every few seconds. Many metals amalgamate with mercury so that in the analysis of metal ions in aqueous solution the DME maintains a fresh surface throughout.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_0e5ef5a7_53c6_4d94_bffd_d0318ea0de6b"></div>

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_b9bece97_a511_4cb9_88a2_b5bd5c5e5d74' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_b9bece97_a511_4cb9_88a2_b5bd5c5e5d74')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b9bece97_a511_4cb9_88a2_b5bd5c5e5d74'; return false;}">ThreeElectrodeElectrochemicalCell</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_e248373f_294f_4ca4_9edf_0ad6653bb64f' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_e248373f_294f_4ca4_9edf_0ad6653bb64f')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_e248373f_294f_4ca4_9edf_0ad6653bb64f'; return false;}">GalvanicCell</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_e931087f_7681_4096_b200_5223bcc47eb4' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_e931087f_7681_4096_b200_5223bcc47eb4')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_e931087f_7681_4096_b200_5223bcc47eb4'; return false;}">ElectrolyticCell</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   composite system in which the supplied electric energy mainly produces chemical reactions or, conversely, in which the energy released by chemical reactions is mainly delivered by the system as electric energy

.. note::

   It is important to distinguish between the conceptual electrochemical cell and the electrochemical device used in practice.

.. tip::

   Model each electrode, electrolyte, and interface explicitly to represent charge transport correctly in simulations or ontological mappings.

.. caution::

   Terminology varies across disciplines; in some contexts 'cell' may refer to the assembled device rather than the electrochemical unit of reaction.

.. warning::

   Do not confuse the physical 'cell' with the manufactured 'device' that embeds it.


----

return false;}">ConductivityCell</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_ec1dce8b_bb46_41a9_b532_6bed381aa557' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ec1dce8b_bb46_41a9_b532_6bed381aa557')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ec1dce8b_bb46_41a9_b532_6bed381aa557'; return false;}">VentedCell</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_c14ae9b3_e4ba_4129_a7b6_afd2d4571de6' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_c14ae9b3_e4ba_4129_a7b6_afd2d4571de6')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c14ae9b3_e4ba_4129_a7b6_afd2d4571de6'; return false;}">HermeticallySealedCell</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_95e4aa95_b7e9_40d7_b78e_4d7dcc31093d' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_95e4aa95_b7e9_40d7_b78e_4d7dcc31093d')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_95e4aa95_b7e9_40d7_b78e_4d7dcc31093d'; return false;}">FlowCell</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   an electrochemical device contains at least one electrochemical cell plus the apparati required to make it work as a practical device (e.g. terminals, container, etc.)

.. note::

   The term refers to the engineered assembly; it must not be conflated with the electrochemical cell itself.

.. tip::

   When documenting a device, identify the number and arrangement of cells and the presence of auxiliary components such as separators, membranes, and power electronics.

.. important::

   Electrochemical devices typically include safety and control subsystems that are not part of the electrochemical cell (e.g. pressure relief, BMS, valves, current collectors).


----

ElectrochemicalHalfCell
-----------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9da958fc_f76d_4654_8a78_99b5f98c118c

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">HalfCell</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a system comprising one electrode in contact with an ionic conductor.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903509' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903509')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903509'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q903509</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-cell' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-cell')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-cell'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-cell</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><div class="restriction-list"><ul><li><a href='#EMMO_e1097637_70d2_4895_973f_2396f04fa204' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_e1097637_70d2_4895_973f_2396f04fa204')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_e1097637_70d2_4895_973f_2396f04fa204'; return false;}">hasProperty</a> some <a href='#electrochemistry_7fc10197_41d9_4c1e_a107_928f03eb2d36' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_7fc10197_41d9_4c1e_a107_928f03eb2d36')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_7fc10197_41d9_4c1e_a107_928f03eb2d36'; return false;}">StandardElectrodePotential</a></li><li><a href='#electrochemistry_3bd08946_4e81_455d_9fca_dc7a5ead9315' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_3bd08946_4e81_455d_9fca_dc7a5ead9315')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_3bd08946_4e81_455d_9fca_dc7a5ead9315'; return false;}">hasElectrolyte</a> some <a href='#EMMO_bc37743c_37c4_4ec7_9d58_d1aae5567352' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_bc37743c_37c4_4ec7_9d58_d1aae5567352')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_bc37743c_37c4_4ec7_9d58_d1aae5567352'; return false;}">Substance</a></li><li><a href='#electrochemistry_578c41e9_ee01_4840_9c8c_04ab6e4e6241' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_578c41e9_ee01_4840_9c8c_04ab6e4e6241')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_578c41e9_ee01_4840_9c8c_04ab6e4e6241'; return false;}">hasElectrode</a> some <a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></li></ul></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_b9522e56_1fac_4766_97e6_428605fabd3e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_b9522e56_1fac_4766_97e6_428605fabd3e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_b9522e56_1fac_4766_97e6_428605fabd3e'; return false;}">HolisticArrangement</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Do not conflate a half-cell (a physical arrangement) with a half-reaction (a formal redox equation component).

.. note::

   A half-cell becomes operational when paired with at least one other half-cell to form an electrochemical cell; the pair allows charge balance through ionic and electronic pathways.

.. warning::

   Do not conflate an ElectrochemicalHalfCell (the combination of one electrode and one electrolyte) with a half-cell device, which is an experimental setup used to measure the properties of an electrode relative to a reference electrode.

.. important::

   A single half-cell cannot sustain continuous current by itself; closed-circuit operation requires a counter half-cell and an external electronic path.

.. note::

   electrochemical reactions occur at electrochemical interfaces

.. note::

   The electrode reaction can also involve other chemical reactions including subreactions on a cell electrode.

.. note::

   any process either caused or accompanied by the passage of an electric current and involving in most cases the transfer of electrons between two substances

Electrode
---------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electronically conductive part in electric contact with a medium of lower electronic conductivity and intended to perform one or more of the functions of emitting charge carriers to or receiving charge carriers from that medium or to establish an electric field in that medium</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">etymology</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">From Greek elektron (amber, electricity) + hodos (way): the way of electricity. Proposed to replace vague poles/plates with a neutral, process-descriptive term. Introduced by Michael Faraday, with support from William Whewell and Whitlock Nicholl.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>

  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Alternative definition: Half-cell consisting of at least one electron conductor and at least one ionic conductor (electrolyte). - Terminology of electrochemical methods of analysis (IUPAC Recommendations 2019)

.. note::

   Electron conductor in an electrochemical cell connected to the external circuit.

.. note::

   In some electroanalytical techniques (conductometry and differential potentiometry), two indicator electrodes are used. For many analytical measurements in cells with current flow, a three-electrode cell is used.

.. note::

   Many types of electrodes are used. These may be classified into groups according to their composition, form and size, and according to their operating mode. See section 4.

.. note::

   The current flow through electrochemical cells may be zero or non-zero. An electrochemical cell with current flow can operate either as a galvanic cell or an electrolytic cell.


----

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_2e3e14f9_4cb8_45b2_908e_47eec893dec8

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrochemical reaction involving the transfer of electrons between electrolyte and electrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.E01960' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.E01960')){window.location.href='https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.E01960'; return false;}">https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.E01960</a></td>

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-02-04' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-02-04')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-02-04'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-02-04</a></td>

    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_a6a69e90_06b5_45b1_83cf_7c0bf39b2914' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a6a69e90_06b5_45b1_83cf_7c0bf39b2914')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a6a69e90_06b5_45b1_83cf_7c0bf39b2914'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalReaction</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_f4a1323a_ce2b_4c1a_b89d_c80170110ed6' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_f4a1323a_ce2b_4c1a_b89d_c80170110ed6')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f4a1323a_ce2b_4c1a_b89d_c80170110ed6'; return false;}">CathodicReaction</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_a0580fa9_5073_44af_b33e_7adbc83892d0' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a0580fa9_5073_44af_b33e_7adbc83892d0')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a0580fa9_5073_44af_b33e_7adbc83892d0'; return false;}">AnodicReaction</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   An interfacial reaction that necessarily involves a charge-transfer step.

.. note::

   The electrode (or interfacial) reaction involves all the processes (chemical reaction, structural reorganization, adsorption) accompanying the charge transfer step.

  <tr>

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>

Electrodeposition
-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f0c24970_4c14_4207_bd78_5f2181a67085

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the process of forming a film or a bulk material using an electrochemical process where the electrons are supplied by an external power supply</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_bafc17b5_9be4_4823_8bbe_ab4e90b6738c' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_bafc17b5_9be4_4823_8bbe_ab4e90b6738c')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_bafc17b5_9be4_4823_8bbe_ab4e90b6738c'; return false;}">IntentionalAgency</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_f4a1323a_ce2b_4c1a_b89d_c80170110ed6' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_f4a1323a_ce2b_4c1a_b89d_c80170110ed6')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f4a1323a_ce2b_4c1a_b89d_c80170110ed6'; return false;}">CathodicReaction</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_a2b92d2e_4431_411e_8da5_a4c08bac2c0e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a2b92d2e_4431_411e_8da5_a4c08bac2c0e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a2b92d2e_4431_411e_8da5_a4c08bac2c0e'; return false;}">Electroplating</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Used in manufacturing, coating, and electrorefining applications.

.. admonition:: Example

   Deposition of metallic zinc from Zn^{2+} ions in an electroplating bath.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_4df84ec1_8a1a_4770_963f_bf48009bd043"></div>

Electrodissolution
------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_4df84ec1_8a1a_4770_963f_bf48009bd043

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the electrochemical dissolution of a material to soluble species</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_49263a32_eca6_4644_8144_0d3b14c26d0a' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_49263a32_eca6_4644_8144_0d3b14c26d0a')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_49263a32_eca6_4644_8144_0d3b14c26d0a'; return false;}">Dissolution</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_a0580fa9_5073_44af_b33e_7adbc83892d0' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a0580fa9_5073_44af_b33e_7adbc83892d0')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a0580fa9_5073_44af_b33e_7adbc83892d0'; return false;}">AnodicReaction</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   It can be regarded as the reversal of electrodeposition.

.. admonition:: Example

   Dissolution of metallic copper as Zn^{2+} during corrosion or anodization.

Electrolysis
------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_e2a1dae1_05e4_4bd1_a39d_0eb10db482bc

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">method of separating and neutralizing ions by an electric current in an electrolytic cell</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">etymology</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">From Greek elektron (electric) + lysis (loosening, dissolution): decomposition by electricity. Part of Faradays systematic terminology built to avoid theoretical commitments. Coined by Michael Faraday with support from William Whewell and Whitlock Nicholl.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>

Electrolyte
-----------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a material in which the mobile species are ions and free movement of electrons is blocked.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">etymology</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">From Greek elektron ('electric') + lyts (, looser): that which is set free or made to pass by electricity; adopted to denote the conducting medium undergoing electrolysis. Coined by Michael Faraday with support from William Whewell and Whitlock Nicholl.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q162908' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q162908')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q162908'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q162908</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
