  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_c6d6c0a1_a06b_437a_978f_a469d3071ca9' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_c6d6c0a1_a06b_437a_978f_a469d3071ca9')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c6d6c0a1_a06b_437a_978f_a469d3071ca9'; return false;}">PolymerElectrolyte</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_15b852b5_19cc_49ab_849f_7df6175fb2be' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_15b852b5_19cc_49ab_849f_7df6175fb2be')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_15b852b5_19cc_49ab_849f_7df6175fb2be'; return false;}">Catholyte</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_865a40fc_2187_4549_a7e1_37aa2458448f' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_865a40fc_2187_4549_a7e1_37aa2458448f')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_865a40fc_2187_4549_a7e1_37aa2458448f'; return false;}">Anolyte</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_0508a114_544a_4f54_a7de_9b947fb4b618' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0508a114_544a_4f54_a7de_9b947fb4b618')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0508a114_544a_4f54_a7de_9b947fb4b618'; return false;}">SolidElectrolyte</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_4e02d727_07fe_41fd_886c_041317342086' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_4e02d727_07fe_41fd_886c_041317342086')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_4e02d727_07fe_41fd_886c_041317342086'; return false;}">BinaryElectrolyte</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_609b340f_3450_4a10_95c2_c457e3eb8a89' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_609b340f_3450_4a10_95c2_c457e3eb8a89')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_609b340f_3450_4a10_95c2_c457e3eb8a89'; return false;}">LiquidElectrolyte</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   A solid electrolyte is a solid material where the predominant charge carriers are ions. For example: NASICON (Na Super Ionic Conductor), which has the general formula Na1+xZr2P3-xSix O12 , 0 < x < 3.

.. note::

   An ionic liquid is an electrolyte composed of a salt that is liquid below 100 C. Ionic liquids have found uses in electrochemical analysis, because their unconventional properties include a negligible vapor pressure, a high thermal and electrochemical stability, and exceptional dissolution properties for both organic and inorganic chemical species.

.. note::

   conducting medium in which the flow of electric current is accompanied by the movement of ions

.. note::

   liquid or solid substance containing mobile ions that render it conductive

.. note::

   substance that provides ions on dissolution in a solvent or on melting


----

    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_7760b241_775f_4be1_b827_59f9bde9e5b2' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_7760b241_775f_4be1_b827_59f9bde9e5b2')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_7760b241_775f_4be1_b827_59f9bde9e5b2'; return false;}">PhotoelectrolyticCell</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   An electrochemical cell that requires input of work to drive the reaction.

.. note::

   Electrochemical cell in which electrical energy is converted into chemical energy.

--------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a2b92d2e_4431_411e_8da5_a4c08bac2c0e

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">Galvanizing</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">process inside an electrolytic cell used to coat a conductive object with a layer of a material</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electroplating' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electroplating')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electroplating'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electroplating</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_f0c24970_4c14_4207_bd78_5f2181a67085' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_f0c24970_4c14_4207_bd78_5f2181a67085')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f0c24970_4c14_4207_bd78_5f2181a67085'; return false;}">Electrodeposition</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The process of depositing a usually thin layer of metal upon a usually metallic substrate (or any other conductor, e.g. graphite), in order to improve the appearance, and/or to change the surface properties of the substrate.

EquilibriumElectrodePotential
-----------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d91940f0_c8b6_4505_9b68_6bf6cfc5c544

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">EquilibriumPotential; NernstPotential; ReversiblePotential</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">potential of an electrode when no electric current flows through the cell and all local charge transfer equilibria across phase boundaries that are represented in the cell diagram (except at possible electrolyte-electrolyte junctions) and local chemical equilibria are established</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reversal_potential' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reversal_potential')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reversal_potential'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reversal_potential</a></td>
  </tr>

------------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_1152ae6b_8b57_4d99_912e_40c6a29342fb

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">FaradaysLaw; FaradaysLawOfElectrolysis</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">mass m of electrochemically-transformed substance is proportional to the charge Q passed, m  Q.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#First_law' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('First_law')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faraday%27s_laws_of_electrolysis#First_law'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faraday%27s_laws_of_electrolysis#First_law</a></td>

   <div id="electrochemistry_60c5b2e5_164a_4ce6_8409_f386f5e50c03"></div>

FaradaysSecondLawOfElectrolysis
-------------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_60c5b2e5_164a_4ce6_8409_f386f5e50c03

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">when the same electric charge (quantity of electricity) Q is passed through several electrolytes, the mass, m_i, of the substances deposited are proportional to their respective chemical equivalent molar mass, M_i/z_i.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#Second_law' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('Second_law')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faraday%27s_laws_of_electrolysis#Second_law'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faraday%27s_laws_of_electrolysis#Second_law</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_9c32fd69_f480_4130_83b3_fb25d9face14' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_9c32fd69_f480_4130_83b3_fb25d9face14')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_9c32fd69_f480_4130_83b3_fb25d9face14'; return false;}">PhysicalLaw</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   m_1/m_2 = (M_1/z_1) / (M_2/z_2)

   An electrochemical cell that spontaneously produces work.

   Electrochemical cell intended to produce electric energy.

---------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_bbb1d95b_72d1_44f6_b07e_a3d7d41ac215

    <td class="element-table-value">a type of electrode specifically designed for gaseous reactants or products or both</td>
  </tr>

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>

    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=485-02-02' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=485-02-02')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=485-02-02'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=485-02-02</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_3663991d_9319_4f7a_922b_f0e428b58801' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_3663991d_9319_4f7a_922b_f0e428b58801')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_3663991d_9319_4f7a_922b_f0e428b58801'; return false;}">PorousElectrode</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543'; return false;}">InertElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_573be62a_5aae_4984_9a51_7c50845493df' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_573be62a_5aae_4984_9a51_7c50845493df')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_573be62a_5aae_4984_9a51_7c50845493df'; return false;}">CardonDioxideElectrode</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_8b40856f_1ca2_4137_9616_7fb624671909' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_8b40856f_1ca2_4137_9616_7fb624671909')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_8b40856f_1ca2_4137_9616_7fb624671909'; return false;}">AirElectrode</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_e2c91edd_dd01_4309_9735_6fe5280261d4' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_e2c91edd_dd01_4309_9735_6fe5280261d4')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_e2c91edd_dd01_4309_9735_6fe5280261d4'; return false;}">OxygenElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   A gas diffusion electrode usually comprises one or more porous layers, like the gas diffusion layer and the catalyst layer.

.. note::

   Gas diffusion electrodes can be gas diffusion anodes or gas diffusion cathodes.

.. note::

   Gas diffusion electrodes can be used in batteries, fuel cells, and electrolyzers.

GasDissolution
--------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0c9017b4_6efd_4e2b_8e24_48b60ebe9315

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the dissolution of molecules from a gas into another phase</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_49263a32_eca6_4644_8144_0d3b14c26d0a' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_49263a32_eca6_4644_8144_0d3b14c26d0a')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_49263a32_eca6_4644_8144_0d3b14c26d0a'; return false;}">Dissolution</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Often leads to efficiency loss or mechanical degradation in electrochemical devices.

.. admonition:: Example

   Absorption of CO into an alkaline electrolyte forming carbonate species.

.. admonition:: Example

   Hydrogen evolution during water electrolysis.

GlassyCarbonElectrode
---------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_057bb143_639c_472b_99ed_ffa1867f6e63

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">GCE</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrode made of glassy carbon material with an intertwined graphitic ribbon structure, formed by pyrolysis of a resol precursor at temperatures up to 3000 C</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543'; return false;}">InertElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   extremely resistant to many chemicals, impermeable to gases and liquids, and has good electrical conductivity, high hardness and strength, and biocompatibility

.. note::

   glassy carbon combines glass-like mechanical characteristics with physical properties similar to graphite, owing to its graphene ribbon structure

.. note::

   one of the most frequently used working electrodes


----

-------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_6fec8cc1_4e6c_428e_8343_6cf3c286a185

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">AuElectrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">foil, wire or disc electrode made of gold which is easily fabricated into a variety of electrode geometries</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><div class="restriction-list"><ul><li><a href='#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee'; return false;}">hasActiveMaterial</a> some <a href='#substance_b3815a7f_f64a_48f6_b0ce_d0032578c699' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('substance_b3815a7f_f64a_48f6_b0ce_d0032578c699')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/chemical-substance#substance_b3815a7f_f64a_48f6_b0ce_d0032578c699'; return false;}">Gold</a></li></ul></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_52547692_f773_4e3f_8c8b_1d9d39bc3c8c' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_52547692_f773_4e3f_8c8b_1d9d39bc3c8c')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_52547692_f773_4e3f_8c8b_1d9d39bc3c8c'; return false;}">GoldBasedElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   At positive potentials, Au forms an oxide and/or chemisorbed oxygen layer, while in the presence of complexing anions, such as chloride or cyanide, it readily undergoes oxidation and dissolution, limiting its working potential range and its applications.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_fa54f95d_b49e_43b5_84c3_35520d0fb2f6"></div>

GouyChapmanModel
----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_fa54f95d_b49e_43b5_84c3_35520d0fb2f6

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">an extension of the Helmholtz model that describes the distribution of ions as a function of distance from the electrode surface to the bulk of the electrolyte</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b'; return false;}">DoubleLayerModel</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   this model fails for highly charged double layers


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_7f168ebc_4c78_459c_9a39_bddaa57e214c"></div>

GrahameModel
------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_7f168ebc_4c78_459c_9a39_bddaa57e214c

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a modification of the Stern model that considers the double layer as three regions separated by the inner Helmholtz plane and the outer Helmholtz plane</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b'; return false;}">DoubleLayerModel</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   proposed by D. C. Grahame in 1947


----

HelmholtzModel
--------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9bc02662_9799_4593_906d_638a841d7352

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a structural representation of the double layer that states that the accumulation of electric charge on the surface of the electrode is balanced by a layer of ions in the electrolyte</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b'; return false;}">DoubleLayerModel</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   proposed by Hermann von Helmholtz in 1853

.. note::

   the first model for the double layer


----

HydrogenElectrode
-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c4a778c7_33da_4e1a_960e_402a210bfeff

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">platinized platinum electrode saturated by a stream of pure gaseous hydrogen</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-16' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-16')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-16'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-16</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a0a619d7_da95_41f0_8bc3_9c19d636d543'; return false;}">InertElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   A platinized platinum electrode consists of a platinum rod covered by compact platinum powder called platinum black.

IncreasingPotentialPulses
-------------------------

    <td class="element-table-value">Pulses of electric potential, of amplitude increasing by a constant increment and with a pulse width of 2 to 200 ms, which are superimposed on a constant initial potential.</td>

IndicatorElectrode
------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f6fcd255_248d_4603_b128_04dab960a676

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrode that responds to one, or more than one, species in the solution being investigated, with no appreciable change of bulk solution composition during the measurement</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907462' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907462')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907462'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907462</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/I03006' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/I03006')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/I03006'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/I03006</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   If processes of interest occur both at the anode and the cathode of a cell (as in differential amperometry or controlled-current potentiometric titration with two indicator electrodes), the cell should be said to comprise two indicator or working electrodes.

.. note::

   This term is typically used in potentiometry.

InterphaseGrowth
----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_402598d9_0eea_405d_b0d0_3b8b79deba6f

  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the process through which the size of an interphase increases over time</td>

  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>

  </table>

.. admonition:: Example

   solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) growth

  </table>

.. note::

   a selective barrier that permits the passage of ions of one sign while preventing the passage of ions of opposite sign.

IonicLiquidElectrolyte
----------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c3f4b34a_0e2c_46f3_baab_4ebd2682d26f

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">IonicLiquid</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">An ionic liquid is an electrolyte composed of a salt that is liquid below 100 C. Ionic liquids have found uses in electrochemical analysis, because their unconventional properties include a negligible vapor pressure, a high thermal and electrochemical stability, and exceptional dissolution properties for both organic and inorganic chemical species.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ionic_liquid' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ionic_liquid')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ionic_liquid'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ionic_liquid</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">dbpediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://dbpedia.org/page/Ionic_liquid' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://dbpedia.org/page/Ionic_liquid')){window.location.href='https://dbpedia.org/page/Ionic_liquid'; return false;}">https://dbpedia.org/page/Ionic_liquid</a></td>

  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_5f9a9411_05f9_4576_acd3_81d7d41cfe98' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_5f9a9411_05f9_4576_acd3_81d7d41cfe98')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_5f9a9411_05f9_4576_acd3_81d7d41cfe98'; return false;}">NonAqueousElectrolyte</a></td>

   represented in IEC cell designations by the letter code Fp

   <div id="electrochemistry_598ae3d0_76e9_429c_a0e1_8694525cb574"></div>

KohlrauschsLaw
--------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_598ae3d0_76e9_429c_a0e1_8694525cb574

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">For any electrolyte A_xB_y, the limiting molar conductivity is expressed as x times the limiting molar conductivity of A^{y+} and y times the limiting molar conductivity of B^{x-}.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3258329' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3258329')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3258329'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3258329</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#Kohlrausch's_law_of_independent_migration_of_ions' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('Kohlrausch's_law_of_independent_migration_of_ions')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molar_conductivity#Kohlrausch's_law_of_independent_migration_of_ions'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molar_conductivity#Kohlrausch's_law_of_independent_migration_of_ions</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_f19ff3b4_6bfe_4c41_a2b2_9affd39c140b' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_f19ff3b4_6bfe_4c41_a2b2_9affd39c140b')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_f19ff3b4_6bfe_4c41_a2b2_9affd39c140b'; return false;}">MaterialLaw</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   proposed by Friedrich Kohlrausch between 1875-1879

.. note::

   valid for dilute solutions

LimitingCurrentDensity
----------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_077de429_ea41_444c_8571_6a832ae62637

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">maximum electric current density that can be achieved for an electrode reaction at a given concentration of a electrochemically active material in the presence of a large excess of supporting electrolyte</td>
  </tr>

LiquidJunction
--------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_634467ad_feed_4979_adb2_877d98fe1768

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">any junction between two electrolyte solutions of different composition.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/L03584' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/L03584')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/L03584'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/L03584</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_50044b99_b858_433b_a32d_23d1e1cf88b2' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_50044b99_b858_433b_a32d_23d1e1cf88b2')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_50044b99_b858_433b_a32d_23d1e1cf88b2'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalInterface</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Across such a junction there arises a potential difference, called the liquid junction potential.

.. note::

   In the operational pH cell the junction is between the test, or pH standard, solution and the filling solution or the bridge solution of the reference electrode.


----

.. raw:: html

MaximumCapacity
---------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b7781ebc_90a7_4f19_997f_aed28dee1b01

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">MaximumStorageCapacity</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the maximum amount of electric charge that can be reversible stored within an electrochemical device</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">typicalUnit</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#AmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('AmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour</a>; <a href='#MilliAmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('MilliAmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26'; return false;}">RatedCapacity</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalQuantity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Manufacturers define the value for 'maximum capacity' as the upper performance limit that a device in a batch will typically achieve. The maximum capacity is larger than the nominal capacity, and acts as an indicator of the spread in performacne in a given batch of devices.

.. caution::

   For real applications, the maximum capacity is affected by environmental conditions, rate of operation, and state-of-heath and can deviate from the reported value.


----

.. admonition:: Example

   Analysis of SEM (or optical) images to gain additional information (image filtering/integration/averaging, microstructural analysis, grain size evaluation, Digital Image Correlation procedures, etc.)

.. admonition:: Example

   In nanoindentation testing, this is the Oliver-Pharr method, which allows calculating the elastic modulus and hardness of the sample by using the load and depth measured signals.

   <div id="electrochemistry_df78745e_f9db_4830_88f0_8ce074fcb8ff"></div>

MercuryElectrode
----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_df78745e_f9db_4830_88f0_8ce074fcb8ff

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">HgElectrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">liquid metal electrode used in polarography</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><div class="restriction-list"><ul><li><a href='#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee'; return false;}">hasActiveMaterial</a> some <a href='#substance_dc5fb846_1824_40f8_9834_81f118aa1c2d' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('substance_dc5fb846_1824_40f8_9834_81f118aa1c2d')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/chemical-substance#substance_dc5fb846_1824_40f8_9834_81f118aa1c2d'; return false;}">Mercury</a></li></ul></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_9fd49892_cf6d_482e_a6c3_5f763948ec29' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_9fd49892_cf6d_482e_a6c3_5f763948ec29')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9fd49892_cf6d_482e_a6c3_5f763948ec29'; return false;}">LiquidMetalElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_b76a778f_253f_4210_a67f_fb6444d0de26' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_b76a778f_253f_4210_a67f_fb6444d0de26')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b76a778f_253f_4210_a67f_fb6444d0de26'; return false;}">DroppingMercuryElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   A mercury film electrode (MFE) or thin mercury film electrode (TMFE) is formed by coating a conducting substrate, usually glassy carbon, with a layer of mercury (thin film, amalgam, or array of microdrops), often by electrodeposition from a solution containing Hg(II). The electrode area is normally in the range of 0.1 to 0.5 cm2 and mercury film thickness typically ranges from 10 to 1000 nm, producing a film of large surface area-to-volume ratio that results in a high analyte pre-concentration during the deposition step of anodic stripping voltammetry. Compared to an HMDE, the MFE provides high sensitivity and resolution; however, it is somewhat less reproducible and more prone to interferences from intermetallic formation and surface-active substances.

.. note::

   Liquid mercury is an ideal electrode material for negative potentials because of its high overpotential for hydrogen evolution (electrochemical reduction of hydroxonium cations from solution). However, mercury is readily oxidized, particularly in the presence of anions that form complexes or that pre- cipitate with Hg(I) or Hg(II) ions, and thus it is not suitable for use at positive potentials. The use of liquid mercury has largely been discontinued because of concerns about the toxicity of the element and its compounds.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_5adb91e0_ffe1_41f3_b779_c6966f65fb0e"></div>

MinimumCapacity
---------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d3c0078e_c1d3_461e_873d_e5c3adf441c5

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">MiniumumAcceptedCapacity</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the minimum acceptable threshold value for the rated capacity of an electrochemical device, as stated by the manufacturer.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">typicalUnit</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#AmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('AmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour</a>; <a href='#MilliAmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('MilliAmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26'; return false;}">RatedCapacity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Manufacturers define the value for 'minimum capacity' as the lower performance limit, ensuring that every device meets a minimum standard. In practice, minimum capacity is often about 95-97% of the nominal capacity, acting as a guaranteed lower bound rather than an exact measurement.

.. caution::

   For real applications, the achieveable minimum capacity is affected by environmental conditions, rate of operation, and state-of-heath and can deviate from the reported value.

NegativeElectrode
-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c94c041b_8ea6_43e7_85cc_d2bce7785b4c

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">NegativePlate</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">for a device having two electrodes, that electrode having the lower electric potential</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907506' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907506')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907506'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907506</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-04' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-04')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-04'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-04</a>; <a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-05' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-05')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-05'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-05</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   by convention, an oxidation reaction occurs during discharge

.. warning::

   The term "anode" is often used interchangably with "negative electrode" even though it only applies while the cell is being discharged. When the cell is being charged the negatve electrode becomes the cathode.

NernstEinsteinEquation
----------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9d7e5fea_a49a_4a19_a8de_8e24c60e420c

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">an equation relating the limiting molar conductivity _m^0  to the ionic diffusion coefficients.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q9325636' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q9325636')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q9325636'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q9325636</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#Nernst%E2%80%93Einstein_equation' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('Nernst%E2%80%93Einstein_equation')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Einstein_relation_(kinetic_theory)#Nernst%E2%80%93Einstein_equation'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Einstein_relation_(kinetic_theory)#Nernst%E2%80%93Einstein_equation</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalRelation</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   \Lambda_m^0 = (F^2/(R*T)) * (v_{+} * z_{+}^2 * D_{+} + v_{} * z_{}^2 * D_{})

NernstEquation
--------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_fe3a6c9a_85b8_4da6_aa4f_71c8de74939e

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">An equation that relates the reduction potential of an electrochemical reaction (half-cell or full cell reaction) to the standard electrode potential, temperature, and activities (often approximated by concentrations) of the chemical species undergoing reduction and oxidation.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q751124' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q751124')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q751124'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q751124</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nernst_equation' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nernst_equation')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nernst_equation'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nernst_equation</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">dbpediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://dbpedia.org/page/Nernst_equation' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://dbpedia.org/page/Nernst_equation')){window.location.href='https://dbpedia.org/page/Nernst_equation'; return false;}">https://dbpedia.org/page/Nernst_equation</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_3d805c2a_4801_440e_9e4d_0fa5585c76ae'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalRelation</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   E_{eq} = E^0 - (R*T/(z*F))*ln(Q)

.. note::

   An expression of the Law of Mass Action.

NominalCapacity
---------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_8abde9d0_84f6_4b4f_a87e_86028a397100

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">the rated capacity that is representative of the typical value associated with a cell as stated by the manufacturer</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">typicalUnit</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#AmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('AmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour</a>; <a href='#MilliAmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('MilliAmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26'; return false;}">RatedCapacity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The value for 'nominal capacity' is provided by manufacturers as an indication of the expected performance of the device under a set of defined nominal conditions. It serves as a benchmark for comparing different devices.

.. tip::

   To ensure meaningful comparisons, nominal capacity values should always be evaluated under matching test conditions.

.. caution::

   While nominal capacity provides a useful reference, actual capacity depends on various factors, including temperature, rate, and state-of-health.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_639b844a_e801_436b_985d_28926129ead6"></div>

NominalVoltage
--------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_639b844a_e801_436b_985d_28926129ead6

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">suitable approximate value of the voltage used to designate or identify a cell, a battery or an electrochemical system</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-31' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-31')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-31'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-31</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_17b031fb_4695_49b6_bb69_189ec63df3ee' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_17b031fb_4695_49b6_bb69_189ec63df3ee')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_17b031fb_4695_49b6_bb69_189ec63df3ee'; return false;}">Voltage</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Nominal voltage is the standardized voltage value assigned to a battery cell or module based on typical operating conditions. It serves as a reference point for battery specifications but does not represent the actual voltage during operation. Actual cell voltage may vary due to factors such as state-of-charge, temperature, and load conditions.

.. caution::

   Nominal voltage may not accurately reflect voltage under extreme loads or temperaturesalways check manufacturer specifications.


----

.. raw:: html

NonSpillableCell
----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c610d869_cc03_44f0_b40d_ca86e945b9c9

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">cell from which electrolyte cannot escape regardless of its orientation</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-16' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-16')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-16'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-16</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalDevice</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   some vented cells or batteries are designed so as to be non-spillable when operated within the limits specified by the manufacturer


----

Overpotential
-------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_1cd1d777_e67b_47eb_81f1_edac35d9f2c6

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">ElectrodePolarization; Overvoltage; PolarizationPotential</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrode potential (E) minus the equilibrium electrode potential (Eeq) of an electrochemical reaction</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overpotential' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overpotential')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overpotential'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overpotential</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/O04358' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/O04358')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/O04358'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/O04358</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-02' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-02')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-02'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-02</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_4f2d3939_91b1_4001_b8ab_7d19074bf845' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_4f2d3939_91b1_4001_b8ab_7d19074bf845')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_4f2d3939_91b1_4001_b8ab_7d19074bf845'; return false;}">ElectricPotential</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalQuantity</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_9ed7210c_c4fa_467b_822d_ba12f885bdf4' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_9ed7210c_c4fa_467b_822d_ba12f885bdf4')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9ed7210c_c4fa_467b_822d_ba12f885bdf4'; return false;}">ConcentrationOverpotential</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_60741c58_a10d_4aa6_bb68_0066a6ff8e30' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_60741c58_a10d_4aa6_bb68_0066a6ff8e30')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_60741c58_a10d_4aa6_bb68_0066a6ff8e30'; return false;}">SurfaceOverpotential</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_03a6ce70_5085_4683_bb4e_fc3c18f7143a' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_03a6ce70_5085_4683_bb4e_fc3c18f7143a')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_03a6ce70_5085_4683_bb4e_fc3c18f7143a'; return false;}">OhmicOverpotential</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_f4fadc4e_ca7d_4e4e_89cf_eacf45b4041e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_f4fadc4e_ca7d_4e4e_89cf_eacf45b4041e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f4fadc4e_ca7d_4e4e_89cf_eacf45b4041e'; return false;}">ReactionOverpotential</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_7fa406b0_512a_4d59_9e0c_5d8aba0103ae' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_7fa406b0_512a_4d59_9e0c_5d8aba0103ae')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_7fa406b0_512a_4d59_9e0c_5d8aba0103ae'; return false;}">ActivationOverpotential</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Overpotential is often divided into different contributions: activation overpotential, ohmic overpotential, and concentration overpotential.

.. note::

   Overpotential is the extra voltage required to drive an electrochemical reaction beyond its thermodynamic equilibrium potential. It arises due to kinetic barriers such as activation energy, mass transport limitations, and charge transfer resistance. Overpotential is a key factor in battery efficiency, electrolysis, and corrosion studies, as it affects reaction rates and energy losses.


----

ParasiticReaction
-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b79d4f9e_5727_4895_8d7f_5fc18d83eb90

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">an unwanted side reaction</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-02-07' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-02-07')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-02-07'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-02-07</a>; <a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-13' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-13')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-13'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-13</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_f47611a2_e081_47f0_b287_3fda5f706154' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_f47611a2_e081_47f0_b287_3fda5f706154')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f47611a2_e081_47f0_b287_3fda5f706154'; return false;}">SideReaction</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   in a galvanic cell, parasitic reactions may cause inefficiencies or loss of performance

.. note::

   Parasitic reactions are a subset of side reactions specifically associated with unwanted charge transfer.

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/P04457' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/P04457')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/P04457'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/P04457</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_c995ae70_3b84_4ebb_bcfc_69e6a281bb88' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_c995ae70_3b84_4ebb_bcfc_69e6a281bb88')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_c995ae70_3b84_4ebb_bcfc_69e6a281bb88'; return false;}">ElectricCurrent</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_aecc6094_c6a5_4a36_a825_8a497a2ae112'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalQuantity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. admonition:: Example

   Typical examples of imposed potential programmes in dynamic voltammetric techniques resulting in peak-shaped responses are linear-scan voltammetry, cyclic voltammetry, ac voltammetry, differential pulse voltammetry, square-wave voltammetry, stripping voltammetry, and derivative techniques.

PlatinumElectrode
-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_2d32a81a_2148_41bd_84fb_467aa8de4a8f

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">PtElectrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">foil, wire, disc, or mesh electrode made of platinum, which is the most commonly used metallic working electrode in electrochemistry</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q20851363' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q20851363')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q20851363'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q20851363</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><div class="restriction-list"><ul><li><a href='#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee'; return false;}">hasActiveMaterial</a> some <a href='#substance_25f6ff4c_53ad_4837_97c4_aa6f06099bb5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('substance_25f6ff4c_53ad_4837_97c4_aa6f06099bb5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/chemical-substance#substance_25f6ff4c_53ad_4837_97c4_aa6f06099bb5'; return false;}">Platinum</a></li></ul></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_d8a9a88e_d437_4fef_bc3c_65a1fe627061' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_d8a9a88e_d437_4fef_bc3c_65a1fe627061')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d8a9a88e_d437_4fef_bc3c_65a1fe627061'; return false;}">PlatinumBasedElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Pt has a very small overpotential for hydrogen evolution, which determines the negative potential limit in protic solvents. Pt adsorbs hydrogen, resulting in hydrogen adsorption/desorption waves. However, the positive potential limit in polar aprotic solvents free of oxygen and water is higher than that for any other commonly used electrode materials. In the presence of water and/or oxygen, Pt forms a film of oxide (and/or chemisorbed oxygen), resulting in potentially interfering waves or peaks.


----

PolarizableElectrode
--------------------

PorousElectrode
---------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_3663991d_9319_4f7a_922b_f0e428b58801

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">porous electrodes consist of porous matrices of a single reactive electronic conductor or a mixture of solids that include essentially non-conducting, reactive materials in addition to electronic conductors. An electrolytic solution fills the void spaces of the porous matrix.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><div class="restriction-list"><ul><li><a href='#EMMO_e1097637_70d2_4895_973f_2396f04fa204' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_e1097637_70d2_4895_973f_2396f04fa204')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_e1097637_70d2_4895_973f_2396f04fa204'; return false;}">hasProperty</a> some <a href='#EMMO_3a6578ac_aee0_43b9_9bc6_1eb208c8c9a9' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_3a6578ac_aee0_43b9_9bc6_1eb208c8c9a9')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_3a6578ac_aee0_43b9_9bc6_1eb208c8c9a9'; return false;}">Porosity</a></li></ul></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></td>

PositiveElectrode
-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_aff732a9_238a_4734_977c_b2ba202af126

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">PositivePlate</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">for a device having two electrodes, that electrode having the higher electric potential</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907518' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907518')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907518'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q120907518</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-05' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-05')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-05'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=151-13-05</a>; <a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-06' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-06')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-06'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-02-06</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_6b1f594f_2c0a_46a0_8805_d6ab08baa75e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_6b1f594f_2c0a_46a0_8805_d6ab08baa75e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_6b1f594f_2c0a_46a0_8805_d6ab08baa75e'; return false;}">TubularPlate</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   by convention, a reduction reaction occurs during discharge

.. warning::

   The term "cathode" is often used interchangably with "positive electrode" even though it only applies while the cell is being discharged. When the cell is being charged the positive electrode becomes the anode.

PositiveElectrodeElectronicConductivity
---------------------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_43f77743_1af6_4a0f_9cc6_285c2a450549

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_916b1863_f417_4b94_9407_9d749ada9ed5"></div>

PotentiometricStrippingAnalysis
-------------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_916b1863_f417_4b94_9407_9d749ada9ed5

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">PSA</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">two-step electrochemical measurement in which 1) material is accumulated at an electrode and 2) the material is removed by chemical reaction or electrochemically at constant current with measurement of electrode potential</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_5548f188_df00_4c05_ae98_7846e92efe36' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_5548f188_df00_4c05_ae98_7846e92efe36')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_5548f188_df00_4c05_ae98_7846e92efe36'; return false;}">CurrentControlledProcess</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   historically for the analysis of metal ions, mercury ions were added to the test solution to form a mercury amalgam when reduced. Alternatively, an HMDE or MFE was used and the oxidizing agent added after amalgam formation. However, the toxicity of mercury and its compounds have all but precluded the present-day use of mercury

.. note::

   the accumulation is similar to that used in stripping voltammetry

.. note::

   the stripping potentiogram shows staircase curves of potential as a function of time. Frequently, the first derivative is displayed (dE/dt=f(t)), as this produces peak-shaped signals. The time between transitions (peaks) is proportional to the concentration of analyte in the test solution

.. note::

   the time between changes in potential in step 2 is related to the concentration of analyte in the solution


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_a9fc3f77_e48e_4bce_b118_044d608722f6"></div>

   <div id="electrochemistry_5a5ef74b_e4a7_4b85_ab21_ae0febebaf58"></div>

PotentiostaticCycling
---------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_5a5ef74b_e4a7_4b85_ab21_ae0febebaf58

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrochemical method where the voltage of an electrochemical device is held constant while measuring the current response over multiple charge-discharge cycles to evaluate its performance and stability</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>

RatedCapacity
-------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">capacity value of a battery [or electrode or electrochemical device] determined under specified conditions and declared by the manufacturer</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-15' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-15')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-15'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-03-15</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">typicalUnit</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#AmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('AmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour</a>; <a href='#MilliAmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('MilliAmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_791c1915_a791_4450_acd8_7f94764743b5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_791c1915_a791_4450_acd8_7f94764743b5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_791c1915_a791_4450_acd8_7f94764743b5'; return false;}">Capacity</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_8abde9d0_84f6_4b4f_a87e_86028a397100' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_8abde9d0_84f6_4b4f_a87e_86028a397100')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_8abde9d0_84f6_4b4f_a87e_86028a397100'; return false;}">NominalCapacity</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_b7781ebc_90a7_4f19_997f_aed28dee1b01' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_b7781ebc_90a7_4f19_997f_aed28dee1b01')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b7781ebc_90a7_4f19_997f_aed28dee1b01'; return false;}">MaximumCapacity</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_d3c0078e_c1d3_461e_873d_e5c3adf441c5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_d3c0078e_c1d3_461e_873d_e5c3adf441c5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d3c0078e_c1d3_461e_873d_e5c3adf441c5'; return false;}">MinimumCapacity</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_73f169de_d189_4d7c_893f_a2549771825c' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_73f169de_d189_4d7c_893f_a2549771825c')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_73f169de_d189_4d7c_893f_a2549771825c'; return false;}">RecoveredCapacity</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_b8d4042d_329a_450f_9088_2fc0e16a8667' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_b8d4042d_329a_450f_9088_2fc0e16a8667')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b8d4042d_329a_450f_9088_2fc0e16a8667'; return false;}">RetainedCapacity</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_372c89d0_adab_4585_9662_33c912acef23' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_372c89d0_adab_4585_9662_33c912acef23')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_372c89d0_adab_4585_9662_33c912acef23'; return false;}">TheoreticalCapacity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The term 'rated capacity' is used by manufacturers to specify the energy storage capability of a product under some controlled test conditions. The value is often determined during a constant current load until the a voltage limit is reached, under controlled temperature conditions. The 'rated capacity' helps to compare performance across different devices and provides a bisis for performing system engineering calculations. It can also be used as a basis for calculating other terms like the C-Rate, state-of-charge, and state-of-health of the device. The rated capacity at beginning of life serves as a reference for capacity-fade analysis during long-term cycling.

.. tip::

   The value of rated capacity should be reported together with information on the conditions under which it was determined (e.g. voltage limits, applied current, temperature).

.. caution::

   The value for rated capacity does not necessarily represent the actual capacity in real-world usage, as factors like temperature, rate, and state-of-health affect the effective capacity.


----

.. raw:: html

.. note::

   Redox reactions include both electrochemical and non-electrochemical processes; when the electron transfer occurs across an electrodeelectrolyte interface the reaction is electrochemical.

ReferenceElectrode
------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_7729c34e_1ae9_403d_b933_1765885e7f29

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
