  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/R05229' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/R05229')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/R05229'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/R05229</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-15' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-15')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-15'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=114-03-15</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_9f466223_e20a_474d_ac4d_6d4b6131c275' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_9f466223_e20a_474d_ac4d_6d4b6131c275')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9f466223_e20a_474d_ac4d_6d4b6131c275'; return false;}">NonPolarizableElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_2a40b878_7d09_49db_91b2_d0ee30192284' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_2a40b878_7d09_49db_91b2_d0ee30192284')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_2a40b878_7d09_49db_91b2_d0ee30192284'; return false;}">StandardHydrogenElectrode</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_6ec59f99_5f26_4a7d_9b90_b52e0f8ad190' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_6ec59f99_5f26_4a7d_9b90_b52e0f8ad190')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_6ec59f99_5f26_4a7d_9b90_b52e0f8ad190'; return false;}">SilverChlorideElectrode</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_83ee23b3_2f5c_4afa_b972_ac85e91d7306' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_83ee23b3_2f5c_4afa_b972_ac85e91d7306')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_83ee23b3_2f5c_4afa_b972_ac85e91d7306'; return false;}">NormalHydrogenElectrode</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_0d9ba00d_04bc_4bdc_85af_3380694f6f68' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0d9ba00d_04bc_4bdc_85af_3380694f6f68')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0d9ba00d_04bc_4bdc_85af_3380694f6f68'; return false;}">ReversibleHydrogenElectrode</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_82b66bfe_ec25_417b_ba65_b631ddaaca0e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_82b66bfe_ec25_417b_ba65_b631ddaaca0e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_82b66bfe_ec25_417b_ba65_b631ddaaca0e'; return false;}">SaturatedCalomelElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Electrode that maintains an essentially constant potential under the conditions prevailing in an electrochemical measurement, and that serves for observation, measurement, or control of the potential of the indicator or working electrode.

.. note::

   In potentiometry, under zero current condition, the essentially constant potential is achieved by ensuring a constant composition of solution in contact with the electrode forming a half-cell. Practical reference half-cells are generally non-polarizable electrodes of the 2nd kind (metal | insoluble salt | ion), constructed so that their electrolyte solutions serve as salt bridges to the solutions under investigation.

.. note::

   Double junction reference electrodes are recommended when the reference electrolyte contains interfering components.

.. admonition:: Example

   The standard hydrogen electrode represents the primary standard in electrochemistry. Elec- trodes of the 2nd kind, such as Ag | AgCl, Hg | Hg2, Cl2, Hg | Hg2SO4, and Hg | HgO, can be used as reference electrodes in aqueous solutions containing ions Cl^{}, SO_4^{2}, and OH^{}, respectively.


----

ResponseTimeAtAnISE
-------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_1a104474_c326_4a29_ac26_26a05ac8f72c

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">Duration between the time when an ion-selective electrode and an external reference electrode (the two completing the ion-selective electrode cell) are brought into contact with a sample solution (or the time at which the activity of the ion of interest in solution is changed) and the first time at which the slope of the cell potential vs. time plot (E/t) becomes equal to a limiting value selected on the basis of the experimental conditions and/or requirements concerning accuracy.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>

RotatingDiskElectrode
---------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_6c421175_477f_45e0_8b6c_c3464f5351c5

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">RDE</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">A disc electrode that is embedded in the centre of a cylinder which rotates in solution around the longitudinal cylinder axis.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3587619' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3587619')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3587619'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3587619</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotating_disk_electrode' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotating_disk_electrode')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotating_disk_electrode'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotating_disk_electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_a8bfac4f_3f30_4e6d_8d8e_34b1eeecb614' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_a8bfac4f_3f30_4e6d_8d8e_34b1eeecb614')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_a8bfac4f_3f30_4e6d_8d8e_34b1eeecb614'; return false;}">RoundElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_7f4d74cd_d0a5_4908_9da9_7629fe419917' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_7f4d74cd_d0a5_4908_9da9_7629fe419917')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_7f4d74cd_d0a5_4908_9da9_7629fe419917'; return false;}">RotatingRingDiskElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   The current is directly proportional to the electrode area and the electrode is uniformly accessible.

.. note::

   The limiting current is given by the Levich equation.

-----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_1900143f_cbc0_415f_9057_9382022a7bfe

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">rotational frequency of a rotating component in a rotating disk electrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_3789d3c5_77f4_456e_b7ed_40e670f47e52' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_3789d3c5_77f4_456e_b7ed_40e670f47e52')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_3789d3c5_77f4_456e_b7ed_40e670f47e52'; return false;}">RotationalFrequency</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalControlQuantity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

   The rotating component can be the main rotating disk or a secondary ring as used in rotating ring disk electrodes.

   This arrangement is largely used in mechanistic studies.

SaltBridge
----------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_637c576e_a50e_47ae_8c74_2024ce4c6d0f

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">means of making electrolytic connection between two half cells without introducing a significant liquid junction potential.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q899119' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q899119')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q899119'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q899119</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_bridge' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_bridge')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_bridge'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_bridge</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">dbpediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://dbpedia.org/page/Salt_bridge' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://dbpedia.org/page/Salt_bridge')){window.location.href='https://dbpedia.org/page/Salt_bridge'; return false;}">https://dbpedia.org/page/Salt_bridge</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_b5ea31c9_bb10_4276_980e_c3eceb1efc82' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_b5ea31c9_bb10_4276_980e_c3eceb1efc82')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b5ea31c9_bb10_4276_980e_c3eceb1efc82'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalComponent</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   A typical construction is a tube of an inert material (e.g. agar agar) filled with a solution containing an electrolyte with approximately equal ion mobilities of the cation and the anion (e.g., KNO3, KCl), with the ends of the tube immersed in the electrolyte solution of the half cells.

SealedCell
----------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_8d3bf304_78e4_4e99_abe1_6ab429e44ed1

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">cell which remains closed and does not release either gas or liquid when operated within the limits specified by the manufacturer</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-17' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-17')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-17'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-17</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0acd0fc2_1048_4604_8e90_bf4e84bd87df'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalDevice</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   a sealed cell may be equipped with a safety device to prevent a dangerously high internal pressure and is designed to operate during its life in its original sealed state

--------

   Membranes and diaphragms are special forms of electrochemical separators.

  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_b79d4f9e_5727_4895_8d7f_5fc18d83eb90' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_b79d4f9e_5727_4895_8d7f_5fc18d83eb90')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b79d4f9e_5727_4895_8d7f_5fc18d83eb90'; return false;}">ParasiticReaction</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. caution::

   Side reactions can lead to degradation, gas formation, or loss of active material.


----

Slurry
------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_13fad803_de44_490d_a77e_c330c9168087

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>

SolidAmalgamElectrode
---------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_65c90d8d_9712_4f3f_b830_d8163ec4cfcc

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">SAE</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrode made of a solid amalgam of an appropriate metal</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><div class="restriction-list"><ul><li><a href='#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee'; return false;}">hasActiveMaterial</a> some <a href='#substance_dc5fb846_1824_40f8_9834_81f118aa1c2d' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('substance_dc5fb846_1824_40f8_9834_81f118aa1c2d')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/chemical-substance#substance_dc5fb846_1824_40f8_9834_81f118aa1c2d'; return false;}">Mercury</a></li></ul></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_5adb91e0_ffe1_41f3_b779_c6966f65fb0e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_5adb91e0_ffe1_41f3_b779_c6966f65fb0e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_5adb91e0_ffe1_41f3_b779_c6966f65fb0e'; return false;}">MetalElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Liquid and paste amalgams can also be used.

.. note::

   Solid amalgam electrodes are electrochemically similar to the hanging mercury drop electrode. Their main advantages are high hydrogen overpotential (similar to liquid mercury); a wide working potential range; the simple mechanical, chemical, and electrochemical regeneration of the surface; a long lifetime; low toxicity of material (comparable with that of dental amalgams); applicability for field measurements; compatibility with flow-through systems; simple construction, without mobile parts; and easy miniaturization.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_0508a114_544a_4f54_a7de_9b947fb4b618"></div>

SolidElectrolyte
----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0508a114_544a_4f54_a7de_9b947fb4b618

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">FastIonConductor; SolidStateElectrolyte</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">definition</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">a solid electrolyte is a solid material where the predominant charge carriers are ions.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_ion_conductor' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_ion_conductor')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_ion_conductor'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_ion_conductor</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_fb0d9eef_92af_4628_8814_e065ca255d59'; return false;}">Electrolyte</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. admonition:: Example

   NASICON (Na Super Ionic Conductor), which has the general formula Na1+xZr2P3-xSix O12 , 0 < x < 3.


----

SolidElectrolyteInterphase
--------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ecf136cb_2584_4cb1_98b7_2d2b3d22e40d

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">altLabel</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">SEI</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">an interfacial layer that forms between an electrode phase and and electrolyte phase, due to the decomposition of the electrolyte</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_d16eec87_c646_4566_bda6_7d3357cda061' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_d16eec87_c646_4566_bda6_7d3357cda061')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d16eec87_c646_4566_bda6_7d3357cda061'; return false;}">PassivationLayer</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_f8e0d532_cf44_403c_9188_e00ee161a3c1' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_f8e0d532_cf44_403c_9188_e00ee161a3c1')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_f8e0d532_cf44_403c_9188_e00ee161a3c1'; return false;}">CathodeElectrolyteInterphase</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   although the definition could apply to any electrode, it is conventionally used to describe interfacial layers that form on the anode of an electrochemical cell.

SquareWavePotentialWaveform
---------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0e33278b_639f_412d_9abd_64c3790026ef

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">Periodic potential where the amplitude alternates at a steady frequency between fixed minimum and maximum values, with the same duration at minimum and maximum.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0a03ce7e_d79f_412e_a103_b5d74de9f4d7'; return false;}">ElectricPotentialSignal</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   In an ideal square wave, the transitions between minimum and maximum are instantaneous.

  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#EMMO_0adabf6f_7404_44cb_9f65_32d83d8101a3' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('EMMO_0adabf6f_7404_44cb_9f65_32d83d8101a3')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#EMMO_0adabf6f_7404_44cb_9f65_32d83d8101a3'; return false;}">Duration</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_c5047d29_4e68_43ee_8355_3e8f05dc70a5'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalControlQuantity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Typically, the duration is defined between the onset of one step and the onset of the next step.

SternModel
----------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_aa5ed981_c11b_4c4f_b1fd_8c432e009484

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">describes the double layer as divided into two parts separated by the Stern plane, located about one hydrated ion radius from the electrode surface</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_ac9723d1_bac0_4109_874e_32849de9299b'; return false;}">DoubleLayerModel</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   proposed by Otto Stern in 1924

  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">typicalUnit</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#AmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('AmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#AmpereHour</a>; <a href='#MilliAmpereHour' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('MilliAmpereHour')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour'; return false;}">https://w3id.org/emmo#MilliAmpereHour</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_9b3b4668_0795_4a35_9965_2af383497a26'; return false;}">RatedCapacity</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. caution::

   The value of the practically achieve able capacity is often much lower than the theoretical value.

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_04f28ce3_251d_429e_aa85_ab3eb45bbcd2"></div>

ThermalRunaway
--------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_04f28ce3_251d_429e_aa85_ab3eb45bbcd2

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">unstable condition arising during constant voltage charge in which the rate of heat dissipation capability, causing a continuous temperature increase with resulting further charge current increase, which can lead to the destruction of the battery</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">IEVReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-54' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-54')){window.location.href='https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-54'; return false;}">https://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=482-05-54</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_19abaccd_43be_4048_965c_e4fb63c5951b' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_19abaccd_43be_4048_965c_e4fb63c5951b')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_19abaccd_43be_4048_965c_e4fb63c5951b'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalPhenomenon</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   in lithium batteries thermal runaway may cause melting of lithium

   <div id="electrochemistry_b9bece97_a511_4cb9_88a2_b5bd5c5e5d74"></div>

ThreeElectrodeElectrochemicalCell
---------------------------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_b9bece97_a511_4cb9_88a2_b5bd5c5e5d74

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrochemical cell with a working electrode, reference electrode, and auxiliary electrode</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_6f2c88c9_5c04_4953_a298_032cc3ab9b77' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_6f2c88c9_5c04_4953_a298_032cc3ab9b77')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_6f2c88c9_5c04_4953_a298_032cc3ab9b77'; return false;}">ElectrochemicalCell</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   Electric current flows between the working and auxiliary electrodes. Electrode potential may be measured between the working and reference electrodes.

.. note::

   The working electrode is the site of interest where the electrochemical process occurs, the reference electrode provides a stable potential, and the auxiliary (counter) electrode completes the circuit.

.. tip::

   A potentiostat can be used to maintain a potential difference between the working and reference electrodes.


----

.. raw:: html

   <div id="electrochemistry_58ad1d22_3803_4c95_a137_207cfebe242a"></div>

WorkingElectrode
----------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_fb988878_ee54_4350_9ee9_228c00c3ad35

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">electrode at which one or more electroactive substances undergo reaction in the solution being investigated</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikidataReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q477099' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q477099')){window.location.href='https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q477099'; return false;}">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q477099</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">wikipediaReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Working_electrode' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Working_electrode')){window.location.href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Working_electrode'; return false;}">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Working_electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">iupacReference</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/W06686' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/W06686')){window.location.href='https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/W06686'; return false;}">https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/W06686</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_0f007072_a8dd_4798_b865_1bf9363be627'; return false;}">Electrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclasses</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_3a77b5e7_9646_4154_bf8f_5f798989e5f3' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_3a77b5e7_9646_4154_bf8f_5f798989e5f3')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_3a77b5e7_9646_4154_bf8f_5f798989e5f3'; return false;}">AnnularWorkingElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   If processes of interest occur both at the anode and the cathode of a cell (as in differential amperometry or controlled-current potentiometric titration with two indicator electrodes), the cell should be said to comprise two indicator or working electrodes.

.. note::

   Te potential of a working electrode is controlled with respect to the reference electrode.

.. note::

   This term is typically used in voltammetry, polarography, amperometry, and coulometry.

ZincElectrode
-------------

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_424bf750_7df5_49b5_ba73_ba74397a166b

.. raw:: html

  <table class="element-table">
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">elucidation</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value">an electrode in which the main active material is zinc metal</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">restrictions</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><div class="restriction-list"><ul><li><a href='#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_860aa941_5ff9_4452_8a16_7856fad07bee'; return false;}">hasActiveMaterial</a> some <a href='#substance_9bd78e1c_a4dc_41b6_8013_adb51df1ffdc' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('substance_9bd78e1c_a4dc_41b6_8013_adb51df1ffdc')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/chemical-substance#substance_9bd78e1c_a4dc_41b6_8013_adb51df1ffdc'; return false;}">Zinc</a></li></ul></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="element-table-key"><span class="element-table-key">subclassOf</span></td>
    <td class="element-table-value"><a href='#electrochemistry_5adb91e0_ffe1_41f3_b779_c6966f65fb0e' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_5adb91e0_ffe1_41f3_b779_c6966f65fb0e')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_5adb91e0_ffe1_41f3_b779_c6966f65fb0e'; return false;}">MetalElectrode</a>, <a href='#electrochemistry_d0a26dc2_fde9_4a11_ac26_7c18499d28a5' onclick="if(!document.getElementById('electrochemistry_d0a26dc2_fde9_4a11_ac26_7c18499d28a5')){window.location.href='https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/electrochemistry#electrochemistry_d0a26dc2_fde9_4a11_ac26_7c18499d28a5'; return false;}">ZincBasedElectrode</a></td>
  </tr>
  </table>

.. note::

   the combination with manganese dioxide and an alkali metal hydoxide electrolyte is designated using IEC electrochemical system letter code L

.. note::

   the combination with nickel oxide hydroxide and an alkali metal hydoxide electrolyte is designated using IEC electrochemical system letter code Z

.. note::

   the combination with oxygen and an alkali metal hydoxide electrolyte is designated using IEC electrochemical system letter code P

.. note::

   the combination with oxygen and an ammonium chloride zinc chloride electrolyte is designated using IEC electrochemical system letter code A

.. note::

   the combination with silver oxide and an alkali metal hydoxide electrolyte is designated using IEC electrochemical system letter code S
